article.headline: Oklahoma State 66, Baylor 48
article.story: WACO, Texas (AP) -- Oklahoma State coach Eddie Sutton has a tough time watching the mental mistakes and turnovers being made by his young team. Imagine being in Baylor coach Scott Drew's position, whose team was playing just its second game of the season. Oklahoma State still had much more experience than the Bears. "Try doing that and playing midseason games, and being competitive in the Big 12," Drew said. "When you play young guys, you're going to have those moments." Drew had four freshman and one sophomore on the court at times Saturday in the Bears' home opener, a 66-48 loss to Oklahoma State (12-5, 2-1 Big 12). After serving an unprecedented NCAA penalty that banned them from any non-conference games and then playing their first game on the road, the Bears (0-2) played on campus for the first time since last March. They got off to a miserable start and never recovered. Baylor missed its first six shots and had five turnovers while Oklahoma State jumped out to a 10-0 lead. For all of Baylor's inexperience, Sutton countered with a lineup that had three freshmen and a sophomore. The Cowboys finished with 21 turnovers, only two less than Baylor. "By the end of the year, I'll have pure white hair from coaching these guys," said Sutton, who has won 793 games and been to eight straight NCAA tournaments. "It will drive you absolutely crazy. Especially with the teams I've had that were really mature." Mamadou Diene, the 7-foot freshman from Senegal, finally scored for Baylor six minutes into the game. Henry Dugat's layup 25 seconds later came after a turnover, but the Bears never got closer than that six-point deficit. Torre Johnson, a junior college transfer, kept making short jumpers and finished with career highs 26 points and 12 rebounds for the Cowboys. Johnson carried OSU during a six-minute span after Baylor's first two baskets. Johnson made five of his team's six field goals in that stretch -- all on jumpers inside 10 feet -- and put the Cowboys up 24-8 with a three-point play with 6:10 left. By halftime, when Oklahoma State led 33-22, Johnson already had 15 points. "They were in a zone and coach emphasized trying to find an open spot. They seemed to be going to sleep a lot on the baseline," said Johnson, who finished 9-of-13 shooting. Johnson is 30-of-45 shooting with 70 points and 29 rebounds in four games since returning from a one-game suspension for violating team policy. Mario Boggan added 12 points and Byron Eaton 10 for the Cowboys, who have won four of their last five games. Freshman Curtis Jerrells led Baylor with 12 points, while Aaron Bruce and Dugat had 11 each. Bruce, the nation's top scoring freshman last season who had 20 points in a 79-61 loss at Texas Tech on Wednesday night, was 3-of-14 shooting. The Bears finished 17-of-52. "We felt like there was a lid on our basket," Drew said. "We made some good passes and had some good offensive rebounds. We'd do something to excite the crowd and then we'd have two or three careless turnovers and miss some layups." Bruce was scoreless and missed his first seven shots until consecutive 3-pointers in a 32-second span right after halftime. After those 3-pointers got Baylor within 35-28, Johnson hit a short baseline jumper. David Monds then had an inside basket and a free throw to put the Cowboys up 40-29, and they maintained a double-digit lead the rest of the game. Baylor began practice in mid-October like everybody else, then had to wait three months to play their first game Wednesday night -- 307 days after being eliminated from last year's Big 12 tournament. About 12 minutes before their home opener, the Bears stood in a circle at midcourt, facing the crowd to take part in the playing of the alma mater with the sparse but enthusiastic crowd. "We're taking big steps now," Dugat said. The Bears were banned from playing non-conference games as part of NCAA penalties for numerous violations under former coach Dave Bliss. The violations were discovered after former player Patrick Dennehy was murdered in the summer of 2003. Former player Carlton Dotson pleaded guilty last year and is serving a 35-year sentence for the death of Dennehy, who was missing for six weeks before his body was found. Dennehy's death sparked a scandal that led to the resignation of Bliss, who school investigators discovered had paid up to $40,000 in tuition for two players and improperly solicited $87,000 from school boosters, among other allegations.
